attributes.description: A dashboard with key metrics about a Microsoft SQL Server instance performance

params.markdown:
### Microsoft SQL Server OpenTelemetry Metrics

This dashboard provides an overview of Microsoft SQL Servers through a visual representation of the data collected by [SQLServer OpenTelemetry Receiver](https://github.com/open-telemetry/opentelemetry-collector-contrib/tree/main/receiver/sqlserverreceiver). It includes:
- Database usage metrics 
- Buffer pool metrics
- Query plan metrics (top queries by elapsed time, compilation rate of query plans)
- Blocking stats (number of queries blocked, and the count of processes in blocked state)

embeddableConfig.description: Number of active user connections to SQL Server. A sudden spike may indicate high application load or connection leaks.
Number of SQL batch requests received per second. Reflects overall query throughput and workload intensity.
Average time (in hours) a data page stays in buffer pool before being flushed. Higher is better; low values may indicate memory pressure.
Percentage of page requests served from memory instead of disk. Higher is better.

Compilations: number of new query plans created.
Recompilations: existing query plans rebuilt due to schema/statistics changes.
High recompilations can hurt performance.

panelsJSON.title: Query Plan Compilations vs Recompilations (per sec)

embeddableConfig.description: Cumulative execution time (in seconds) for SQL statements. Useful for identifying long-running queries.
Total CPU time (in seconds) consumed by SQL Server queries. Useful for identifying CPU-intensive workloads
Number of lock requests per second that waited. Frequent waits may indicate contention or blocking issues.
Number of processes currently blocked by other transactions. Persistent blocking can degrade application performance.
